Prepositions in Adjective Clauses

When describing something or someone in an adjective clause, we can sometimes leave out the relative pronoun (who, which, that, etc.) 
and use the preposition with.

It's the boy. He had dark hair. 
It's the boy who has dark hair.
It's the boy with dark hair.

It's a phone. It has a great camera.
It's a phone that has a great camera.
It's a phone with a great camera.
